description: Oh, hey there! Pull up a chair - let's have a chat.  <3  All of these photos are me in different stages of my life - from 2013 Chelsea on the left to September 2017 Chelsea on the right. Different times, places, and journeys, but they're all me.  And while there's nothing necessarily wrong with my physique in any of them, I've faced some extreme physical and psychological challenges in every version  ... of myself that I have taken on. I've endured approving and disapproving comments on every end of the spectrum, regardless of what shape I'm in. I've had people tell me I don't need to work out or diet or make the "healthy choice" while embodying every single one of these people photographed. I've heard that just one more day of drinking and/or indulging wont hurt my goals - I've heard this hundreds of times. Sometimes even from myself.  On the left, I've heard that I don't need to lose weight and I've also heard I could stand to lose 15lbs. On the right, I've heard I that I would look healthier if I gained 15lbs. I've heard my physique is unattractive because I'm too soft or too big or too thin or too muscular. I've had people tell me they're worried about my health without learning about anything I'm doing. I've had people tell me I'm starving myself while I'm eating 2,000 calories a day and/or say nothing when I've gone on 1,000 calorie crash diets.   I've endured unsolicited comments about my food. It's OH SO healthy when it's salad and it's a big fucking deal when it's pizza. I've received all kinds of advice about carbs and fats and alcohol from people who also have no interest in hearing my goals, my process, and/or my progress.   The point is - if you want to make a change, you have to listen to your body and put yourself and your health first, not the opinions of others. If it's losing weight, gaining weight, gaining muscle, running a marathon, learning to lift, learning to have more balance, or any other goal for you, you're going to endure people in your path whom either want to derail you or make you fit into their box of what is healthy or attractive to them. This will 100% happen, and it can be incredibly discouraging and emotionally draining.  If you have goals, physically or otherwise, find people who motivate and empower you and put blinders on to the rest. You have to live with yourself for the rest of your life - make it the best version of you that you can and surround yourself with people who want that for you too.   <3  On a lighter note, I have received so, SO much positivity from you all on this journey and a million questions! Rather than writing the email essays I've been starting and never finishing, I'm thinking of making a Q&A video to answer any and all of the fitness/nutritional questions you guys have in hopes of helping you on your path! Feel free to message me or comment below and I'll see if I can get something up this weekend.  <3  Otherwise, thank you so much for being part of my team and supporting me through this crazy year so far!
